hands_on_practices.solution:
We test whether the two sites have different mean nickel concentrations using a two-sample t-test at confidence level 0.95 (two-tailed). Let $n_{A}=5$, $n_{B}=6$. The null hypothesis is $H_{0}:\mu_{A}=\mu_{B}$ and the alternative is $H_{1}:\mu_{A}\neq\mu_{B}$.

Compute sample means:
$$\bar{x}_{A}=\frac{45.2+48.1+46.5+42.9+44.8}{5}=\frac{227.5}{5}=45.5,$$
$$\bar{x}_{B}=\frac{40.8+41.5+42.1+39.9+41.1+40.2}{6}=\frac{245.6}{6}=\frac{614}{15}\approx 40.933\dots.$$
Thus the mean difference is
$$\bar{x}_{A}-\bar{x}_{B}=45.5-\frac{614}{15}=\frac{137}{30}\approx 4.566\dots.$$

Compute sample variances using $s^{2}=\frac{\sum (x-\bar{x})^{2}}{n-1}$. For Site A, the squared deviations sum to $151/10$, so
$$s_{A}^{2}=\frac{151/10}{5-1}=\frac{151}{40}.$$
For Site B, the squared deviations sum to $10/3$, so
$$s_{B}^{2}=\frac{(10/3)}{6-1}=\frac{2}{3}.$$

Using the pooled-variance two-sample t-test (so that the provided critical t-value table with $\nu=n_{A}+n_{B}-2$ applies), the pooled variance is
$$s_{p}^{2}=\frac{(n_{A}-1)s_{A}^{2}+(n_{B}-1)s_{B}^{2}}{n_{A}+n_{B}-2}
=\frac{4\cdot \frac{151}{40}+5\cdot \frac{2}{3}}{9}
=\frac{\frac{151}{10}+\frac{10}{3}}{9}
=\frac{553}{270}.$$
The standard error of the difference is
$$\mathrm{SE}=\sqrt{s_{p}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n_{A}}+\frac{1}{n_{B}}\right)}
=\sqrt{\frac{553}{270}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{5}+\frac{1}{6}\right)}
=\sqrt{\frac{553}{270}\cdot \frac{11}{30}}
=\sqrt{\frac{6083}{8100}}.$$
Therefore the t-statistic is
$$t=\frac{\bar{x}_{A}-\bar{x}_{B}}{\mathrm{SE}}
=\frac{\frac{137}{30}}{\sqrt{\frac{6083}{8100}}}
=\frac{411}{\sqrt{6083}}
\approx 5.27.$$

The degrees of freedom are $\nu=n_{A}+n_{B}-2=9$. From the provided table, the two-tailed critical value at confidence 0.95 (significance 0.05) for $\nu=9$ is $t_{0.025,9}=2.262$. Since $|t| \approx 5.27 > 2.262$, we reject $H_{0}$ and conclude that there is a statistically significant difference in mean nickel concentrations between the two sites. The correct choice is the statement that the calculated t-value exceeds the critical t-value and thus indicates significance.
